{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f11cacfe-16f8-4c35-901c-b7b22a98dd8d","content":"Here's what you need for NativeAOT crash dump collection:\n\n**Environment variables** (on your container):\n\n```yaml\nenv:\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump\n    value: \"1\"\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpType\n    value: \"4\"                        # 1=Mini, 2=Heap, 3=Triage, 4=Full\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgMiniDumpName\n    value: \"/dumps/core.%t.%p\"        # %t=timestamp, %p=PID\n  - name: DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath\n    value: \"/opt/tools/createdump\"    # Required for NativeAOT (no bundled createdump)\n```\n\n**Pod spec changes:**\n\n```yaml\nspec:\n  containers:\n    - name: your-app\n      # ... existing config ...\n      securityContext:\n        capabilities:\n          add: [\"SYS_PTRACE\"]         # createdump needs ptrace access\n      volumeMounts:\n        - name: crash-dumps\n          mountPath: /dumps\n  volumes:\n    - name: crash-dumps\n      emptyDir:\n        sizeLimit: 4Gi               # adjust to your memory footprint\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`DOTNET_DbgCreatedumpPath`** is essential for NativeAOT since the runtime doesn't bundle `createdump`.\n- **`SYS_PTRACE`** capability is required — without it, `createdump` will silently fail.\n- **`emptyDir`** works for transient collection; swap to a **PersistentVolumeClaim** if you need dumps to survive pod restarts.\n- Dump type `4` (Full) gives the most detail but produces large files. Use `2` (Heap) or `1` (Mini) if space is tight.\n- The `%t.%p` pattern prevents overwrites on repeated crashes.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"bce455c6-82b2-4b20-b912-33c6b84dd5c3","outputTokens":484,"requestId":"7850:1971A6:478B3F:52F5DC:69FA9DBB"},"id":"b60ec068-dc4f-47fd-8585-753477bd2de6","timestamp":"2026-05-06T01:47:52.206Z","parentId":"75ba1ae0-4d7b-4a8d-b234-2a54274e1516"}
